ce:section.ce:para:
Carbon nanotubes (CNTs) have been recognized as cutting-edge nanoprobes due to their remarkable structural, mechanical, and optoelectronic characteristics. They are ideally suited for biosensing applications due to their fast electron transfer rate, sensitivity, high conductivity, and excellent chemical stability. The immobilization of biomolecules on the surface of carbon nanotubes is a crucial aspect of CNT-based biosensors [72]. This process enhances the identification and signal transduction, improving the biosensor’s overall performance. Depending on their transduction mechanisms and target identification abilities, these biosensors can be broadly divided into optical biosensors and electrochemical and electronic CNT-based biosensors [73]. Carbon nanotubes (CNTs) have been widely recognized as remarkable materials that strengthen electron transport; thus, they are an ideal candidate for integrating electrochemical and electronic biosensors. Many glucose biosensors that use glucose oxidase conjugation with carbon nanotubes have been created. Zhu et al. (2014) used carbon nanotube non-woven fabrics (CNTFs) to identify glucose in a solution of polyvinyl alcohol that had been infused with glucose oxidase [74]. When it comes to electrochemical glucose sensing, the Gaitan Group has highlighted how the surface chemistry and structure of glucose oxidase-coated MWCNT play a significant role [75]. In addition, nitric oxide and epinephrine electrochemical biosensors have been developed based on CNTs [76]. Recently, Yan et al. created an electrochemical biosensor via in-situ modification of CNTs to detect various biomarkers, specifically C-reactive protein (CRP), carbohydrate antigen 125 (CA125), and carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) in human serum plasma (
                           Fig. 6

                           ). It demonstrated exceptional electrochemical performance due to the synergistic interaction of pCNTs nanomaterial, aptamer, and horseradish peroxidase-labeled (HRP) antibody. It has the potential for point-of-care testing (POCT) in early diagnosis of illness and biological analysis [77].

Composite scaffolds are designed to accommodate many cell types while facilitating the unimpeded flow of natural biochemical processes. This enables stem cells to develop into adult tissue that resembles the native organ tissue [85]. In this view, CNTs have proven effective at stimulating stem cell differentiation, making them a promising substrate for tissue engineering scaffolds [86]. Collagen and polymer-based functionalized carbon nanotubes (F-CNT) serve as scaffolds in tissue engineering [87]. F-CNT promotes the generation of osteoblastic cells, which are crucial for bone formation (
                           Fig. 7

                           ). The in-vivo investigation indicated better compatibility with bone tissue and successful restoration of periosteal tissue. Moreover, this substance is capable of interacting harmoniously with blood and other bodily tissues [88]. Oxygen-containing functional groups in CNTs increase their ability to adhere to platelets, enhance their anti-coagulation properties, and improve their performance as implants [89]. Three primary techniques are employed in the production of CNTs: π-conjugation of the group by covalent bonding, encasing the nanotube with functional molecules and injecting molecules into the internal cavity. More recently Szymański et al. (2023) conducted research that explored the use of hyaluronic acid (HA) and multi-walled carbon nanotubes (MWCNTs) as bio-ink additives in 3D bioprinting cartilage structures [90]. This tissue engineering technique, known as 3D bioprinting, enables the exact localization of cell-enriched biomaterials and the replication of tissue-specific architectures that can repair, sustain, or enhance damaged tissue via 3D scaffolding [91,92].

A novel method for repairing or replacing damaged tissues through the use of biomaterials is known as tissue engineering [136]. Numerous avenues can be pursued for the prospective application of these systems as components of intelligent surgical instruments, implants, or bone scaffolds [137]. For the purpose of tissue engineering, NDs exhibit suitable features, such as resilience, support adherence, roughness, and thermal stability. The synthesis of such agents was carried out by Grausova and coworkers, who utilized NDs as a matrix on osteoblast-like MG 63 cells. When it came to adherence and development of cells in cultures, NDs proved to be an excellent support system. The research demonstrated that the utilization of NDs in tissue engineering yielded encouraging outcomes, particularly with regard to their potential applications as implantable surface bone materials [138]. According to Eivazzadeh-Keihan and colleague’s findings, a number of different CNMs, including NDs, have the potential to be utilised in bone and tissue engineering. Scientists claimed that the NDs had a good impact due to their improved mechanical properties and biocompatibility. This was demonstrated by the positive immune response that was exhibited towards the implanted composites [139]. Zhang et al. constructed a specialized bone scaffold utilizing PLLA polymer and octadecylamine-functionalized nanodiamonds (ND-ODA) (
                           Fig. 9

                           ). The scaffolds exhibited fluorescence and stability due to the presence of the ND component. Furthermore, they showed no adverse effects on cell proliferation and were deemed safe. This study demonstrated that combining ND-ODA/PLLA with murine osteoblast (7F2) cells for over one week reduced adverse effects.

The development of new biosensors that are both highly sensitive and selective has garnered a lot of attention on a global scale in the past few years. Biosensor research and development has been significantly impacted by the rapid evolution of nanomaterials in recent years. According to current investigations, graphene's exceptional electron transport characteristic and large surface area indicate that graphene-related materials can enhance electron transfer between enzymes and electrodes and therefore be used as promising biosensing candidates [146,147]. Both noncovalent and covalent bonding can be used to attach enzymes to electrodes modified with graphene materials. Prathish and colleagues have created and contrasted different modified electrodes using graphene materials functionalized with basic or acidic groups, nitrogen-doped graphene (NG), and composite materials consisting of NG, the conducting polymer poly(3,4-ethylenedioxythiophene) (PEDOT), and the redox polymer poly (PNR). This finding reveals that the N-graphene-modified GCE outperforms the others in terms of sensitivity because of its n-type semiconductor-like characteristics. This is because it can identify nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) and flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), which are cofactors in enzymes that are based on oxidase and dehydrogenase, respectively [148]. Research on graphene-based nonenzymatic biosensors has also been conducted globally, in addition to graphene-based enzymatic biosensors. In a recent study, Balamurugan et al. presented a unique approach for synthesizing a core–shell hybrid of iron nitride nanoparticles and nitrogen-doped graphene (FeN NPs/NG) using a one-step synthesis technique (
                           Fig. 10

                           ). Due to its large surface area and superior conductivity, an increase in electrocatalytic activity for the direct electrochemical oxidation of NADH was seen in the developed core–shell hierarchical nanostructure. In its unchanged form, the enzyme-less sensor has a rapid reaction time of less than 3 s, a low detection limit of 25 mM, and a broad linear range from 0.4 to 718 µM with a sensitivity of 0.028 µA (µM−1 cm−2). Investigations into human blood serum also revealed that the hierarchical nanostructure of FeN NPs/NG core–shell showed great promise as an electrochemical biosensor due to its high sensitivity, exceptional selectivity, and excellent stability [149]. The researchers from these findings discovered that the electrodes enhanced with carbon nanomaterials provide an amazing platform for simultaneous sensing in minimal sample volumes [150].

The remarkable chemical and physical characteristics of GQDs have made them highly promising in the field of nanomedicine. Nanomedicines, such as radioisotopes and chemotherapeutics, have been explored for their potential in cancer treatments and diagnosis. This is due to their remarkable physicochemical properties, which include a high surface area to volume ratio, effective tracking capabilities, low toxicity, strong hydrophilicity, stable inherent fluorescence, and functional groups on the surface. In addition, recent studies have also showed that GQDs are capable of effectively accelerating the nuclear accumulation of DNA-interfering pharmaceuticals. This results in a significant increase in the DNA cleavage activity and cytotoxic profile of these agents and an increase in the chemotherapeutic efficacy of these drugs [195,196]. As a result of these remarkable biological characteristics, which show that GQDs are better than tailored graphene/GO, and numerous other nanoparticle-based delivery methods, various GQD-based drug delivery systems have been identified for cancer treatment. To minimize the systemic toxicity and unwanted side effects commonly linked to traditional chemotherapy, GQD-based systems have been utilised to deliver medicines and modified with tumor-targeting ligand units. These ligand units have the capability to selectively identify cancer receptors located on the surface of cells and trigger receptor-mediated endocytosis. In the study conducted by Sui et al., the investigation focused on how graphene quantum dots (GQDs) could improve the anticancer effects of cisplatin. Cisplatin, a chemotherapeutic agent, has proven effective in treating various human cancers, such as bladder, head, neck, lung, ovarian, and testicular cancers [197]. However, its usage is often associated with numerous adverse side effects, including severe kidney problems, gastrointestinal disorders, lowered infection resistance, and drug resistance [198]. The investigators observed that the co-administration of cisplatin and GQDs enhanced the cytotoxic effects of the pharmaceuticals in several types of cancerous cell lines [199]. Nonetheless, this effect was not noted in the normal cells that were investigated during the investigation. Compared to drug alone, the cisplatin/GQD system arrested more cells in the G2/M phase and caused significant cell nuclear fragmentation and condensation. In a different study, Wang et al. employed GQDs as nanocarriers to boost the anticancer efficacy of doxorubicin (DOX), a potent antineoplastic drug that is frequently used to treat of numerous prevalent human malignancies, such as breast cancer, soft both aggressive non-Hodgkin lymphoma and tissue sarcomas [200]. Next, in a study, by Wang et al., a detailed targeted system based on GQDs that could transport DOX to cancer cells through folic acid (FA) serving as the targeting ligand is investigated. It states that as a result of π-π interaction, the 2.3 nm GQDs, which were produced from carbon black by treating it with nitric acid, were loaded with DOX and modified with FA via amide bond formation between the amine group of FA and the carboxylic groups of GQDs. The authors proved that the FA-functionalized nanoparticles could keep the ligand's cell-recognition ability after drug loading. Biological experiments conducted in a controlled environment on HeLa cells demonstrated that the cells took up the nanosystems by receptor-mediated endocytosis and successfully delivered the medication to their intended targets. Results showed that the system could distinguish between cancer cells and healthy cells, significantly reducing cytotoxicity towards non-target cells [201]. Recently, Lei et al. developed GQDs that suppress tumor growth by selectively damaging the DNA of cancer cells. The amine-functionalized GQDs were modified with nucleus-targeting TAT peptides (TAT-NGs) and further grafted with cancer-cell-targeting folic acid (FA) modified PEG via disulfide linkage (FAPEG-TNGs) (
                           Fig. 13

                           ). The resulting FAPEG-TNGs exhibited good biocompatibility, nucleus uptake, and cancer cell targeting and showed significant therapeutic efficacy against HeLa tumor xenografts in both in vitro and in vivo conditions. FA-PEG units provided protection, resulting in FAPEG-TNGs exhibiting significant biocompatibility in blood circulation and targeted delivery to the tumor site, facilitated by folic acid recognition. The remarkable therapeutic efficacy resulting from the targeted interaction between GQD nanoparticles and the cancer cell nucleus, as identified in this study, will be highly beneficial for the design and development of chemotherapeutic nanoparticles for clinical applications. [202]. Additionally, researchers were able to accomplish the simultaneous specific labelling of cells, targeted drug delivery, and real-time monitoring of cellular uptake because GQDs had an inherent fluorescence that allowed us to easily observe their cell movement in real-time without the need for additional dyes [192].
